{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"585e7308-26a5-4237-a6f9-75343dc9c998","content":"Here's the analysis of **EvalHeavy.csproj** — I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns**:\n\n---\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via `System.IO.File` during evaluation is **synchronous and blocks the MSBuild engine**. This runs on every evaluation (builds, IDE loads, design-time). Move this to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs at execution time.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree**. This gets exponentially worse if folders like `node_modules` or `.git` exist. Add the pattern to `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob to specific extensions.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (line 6 → 3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. At 3 levels this is manageable, but it compounds — especially if these chains grow. Consider flattening or consolidating shared settings into fewer files.\n\n---\n\n**Priority:** Issue #1 (file I/O) is the most impactful, followed by #2 (glob). The import chain (#3) is low-severity here but worth watching in larger repos.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eff5a494-f79e-423b-a8b9-c53d25d9b741","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues in this project.\n\nThe issues I see:\n\n1. **File I/O property function**: `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` - This reads a file during evaluation, which is expensive because evaluation runs synchronously and this blocks the MSBuild engine.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` - This is an overly broad glob that walks the entire directory tree looking for all files. This is particularly expensive if the directory contains `node_modules`, `.git`, or other large trees.\n   \n3. **Deep import chain**: The project imports through three levels of property files, and while that's not extreme, it compounds the evaluation time when combined with the other expensive operations happening at each level.","outputTokens":648},"id":"e22fe518-e69d-4f76-9901-b71735587365","timestamp":"2026-04-07T16:01:32.791Z","parentId":"0f91caf5-8c7c-4e24-9e0f-03b9e51e83c7"}
